---
import DemoPageLayout from '../../layouts/DemoPageLayout.astro';
import ArrayFactorDemo from '../../components/demos/ArrayFactorDemo';
import KatexEq from '../../components/ui/KatexEq';
---

<DemoPageLayout
  title="Array Factor Demo"
  domain="antennas"
  difficulty="intermediate"
  description="Visualize how a linear phased array steers its beam by controlling element count, spacing, and progressive phase shift."
>
  <div slot="intro">
    <p>
      A phased array antenna consists of N radiating elements arranged in a line with spacing d.
      By applying a progressive phase shift &beta; between adjacent elements, the beam can be steered
      electronically &mdash; no mechanical movement required.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <strong>Array Factor</strong> (AF) describes the combined radiation pattern of the array
      as a function of observation angle &theta;. It depends only on the geometry and phase &mdash; not
      on the element type itself.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div slot="equations">
    <KatexEq display={true} client:only="react">
      {"AF(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=0}^{N-1} e^{\\,j n \\psi}"}
    </KatexEq>
    <KatexEq display={true} client:only="react">
      {"\\psi = kd\\cos\\theta + \\beta, \\qquad k = \\frac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}"}
    </KatexEq>
  </div>

  <ArrayFactorDemo client:only="react" dataUrl="/data/array-factor/default.json" />

  <div slot="interpretation">
    <p>
      <strong>Increasing N</strong> narrows the main lobe (higher directivity) and reduces sidelobe levels.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Increasing d beyond &lambda;/2</strong> causes grating lobes &mdash; additional main lobes
      where phase accumulation completes a full 2&pi; cycle.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Phase shift &beta;</strong> steers the main lobe: &beta; = &minus;kd&middot;cos(&theta;&#8320;)
      points the beam at &theta;&#8320;.
    </p>
  </div>
</DemoPageLayout>
